Sprint 1: Analysis & Source Identification
🎯 User Story 1: Source System Analysis

Description:
Analyze SmartSignal data structures to understand entities, relationships, and ingestion feasibility.

Acceptance Criteria:

SmartSignal entities identified (assets, sensors, events)
Data access method confirmed (API / DB / file)
Sample datasets collected
Data frequency and latency documented

Risks:

Limited access to SmartSignal APIs
Incomplete metadata from source
Dependency on SME availability
🎯 User Story 2: Connection Establishment

Description:
Establish secure connectivity between SmartSignal and Azure environment for data extraction.

Acceptance Criteria:

Connection configured via ADF (Linked Service)
Authentication method validated (OAuth / key / VPN)
Test data extraction successful
Network/firewall rules configured

Risks:

Firewall/network restrictions
Credential approval delays
API throttling
🎯 User Story 3: Source-to-Target Mapping Document

Description:
Define mapping between SmartSignal data fields and Chevron data lake schema.

Acceptance Criteria:

Field-level mapping completed
Data types and formats defined
Timestamp format documented
Asset identifier fields identified
Stakeholder approval obtained

Risks:

Ambiguity in field definitions
Changing requirements
Missing source documentation
🟦 Sprint 2: Ingestion Layer (Bronze)
🎯 User Story 4: Raw Data Ingestion Pipeline

Description:
Implement ingestion pipeline to load SmartSignal data into raw data lake layer.

Acceptance Criteria:

ADF pipeline created
Incremental load implemented (watermark-based)
Data stored in ADLS (Parquet/Delta)
Metadata columns added (ingestion timestamp, source system)

Risks:

High data volume impacting performance
Extraction failures
Schema drift
🎯 User Story 5: Incremental Load Mechanism

Description:
Implement incremental data ingestion to process only new or changed data.

Acceptance Criteria:

Watermark column identified and applied
Historical backfill supported
No duplicate ingestion
Retry/restart logic implemented

Risks:

Incorrect watermark logic leading to data loss/duplication
Late-arriving data issues
Source inconsistencies
🟦 Sprint 3: Asset Mapping (Bigfoot Alignment)
🎯 User Story 6: Asset Mapping Table Creation

Description:
Create mapping between SmartSignal asset identifiers and Bigfoot asset identifiers.

Acceptance Criteria:

Mapping table created
All available SmartSignal assets mapped
Unmapped assets identified and logged
Historical tracking supported (if required)

Risks:

Incomplete mapping data
Complex mapping relationships
Frequent changes in asset hierarchy
🎯 User Story 7: Mapping Validation Framework

Description:
Implement validation to ensure correctness and completeness of asset mapping.

Acceptance Criteria:

Mapping coverage metrics generated
Unmapped assets captured in exception table
Data quality rules implemented
Stakeholder validation completed

Risks:

Low mapping coverage delaying downstream work
Manual intervention required
Dependency on external master data team
🟦 Sprint 4: Transformation Layer (Silver)
🎯 User Story 8: Timestamp Standardization

Description:
Standardize timestamps across all SmartSignal data to a common format (UTC).

Acceptance Criteria:

All timestamps converted to UTC
Timezone handling documented
Standard format applied (ISO 8601)
No invalid or null timestamps

Risks:

Incorrect timezone handling
Data inconsistencies across sources
Precision loss
🎯 User Story 9: Data Transformation Pipeline

Description:
Transform raw SmartSignal data into structured, standardized format.

Acceptance Criteria:

Transformation logic implemented in Databricks
Asset mapping applied
Data cleaned and normalized
Output stored in Silver layer

Risks:

Performance issues with large datasets
Complex/nested data structures
Schema evolution challenges
🟦 Sprint 5: Curated Layer (Gold)
🎯 User Story 10: Curated Data Model

Description:
Design and implement curated data model aligned with Bigfoot asset structure.

Acceptance Criteria:

Data model finalized (narrow/wide schema)
Bigfoot asset ID used as standard key
Partitioning strategy implemented
Optimized Delta tables created

Risks:

Suboptimal data model design
High cardinality affecting performance
Changing reporting requirements
🎯 User Story 11: Data Quality & Validation

Description:
Implement data quality checks to ensure reliability of curated datasets.

Acceptance Criteria:

Null and duplicate checks implemented
Outlier detection rules applied
Error records stored separately
Data quality reporting enabled

Risks:

Over-restrictive validation rules
Missing business validation logic
Increased processing overhead
🟦 Sprint 6: Orchestration & Deployment
🎯 User Story 12: Pipeline Orchestration

Description:
Orchestrate end-to-end data pipelines for automated execution.

Acceptance Criteria:

ADF pipelines trigger transformation jobs
Dependency sequencing implemented
Retry and failure handling configured
Monitoring and logging enabled

Risks:

Inadequate failure handling
Scheduling conflicts
Monitoring gaps
🎯 User Story 13: Production Deployment

Description:
Deploy pipelines and data models to production environment.

Acceptance Criteria:

CI/CD pipeline implemented
Environment separation (Dev/QA/Prod)
Security and access controls configured
SLA and monitoring defined

Risks:

Deployment failures
Environment inconsistencies
Security misconfiguration
